  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">One of our goals is to determine the innermost location r∗ m [see Eq. (3)] of the confining mirror which allows the extraction of rotational energy from spinning Kerr black holes. (This critical radius also marks the boundary between stable and unstable composed black-hole-mirror-field configurations.) As discussed above, the numerical results of [14] indicate that, rapidly-rotating black holes are characterized by the smallest (innermost) stationary mirror radii. We therefore focus our attention on these near-extremal black holes</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">31</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Below we shall see that equatorial field modes with l = m ≥ 2, the modes we shall be interested in in this study, are characterized by this property</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">32</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">One can choose δ > 0 without loss of generality</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">33</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that the resonance condition (21) for the stationary confined states is expressed in terms of the dimensionless ratio xstat m /τ</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">34</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the relation -1 = eiπ(2n-1) which implies ln(-1) = iπ(2n - 1), where n is an integer</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">35</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">We find from (27) that modes with n ≤ 0 are characterized by xstat m /τ &lt; 10. These modes violate the assumption (23) and thus should not be regarded as physical ones. [It is worth emphasizing again that the analytical formula (27) for the critical (stationary) mirror radii is valid in the regime τ ≪ xstat m ≪ 1, see Eqs. (18) and (23)]</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth emphasizing that, finding the roots of the characteristic equation (21) is a much easier task than the Runge-Kutta numerical solution of the Teukolsky wave equation presented in [14]. In addition, as we shall discuss below, another notable advantageous of our analysis lies in the fact that, the characteristic resonance condition (21) can easily be solved for asymptotically large values of the harmonic indexes (l, m). Below we shall be interested in this asymptotic (eikonal) regime</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">37</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">One of our goals is to determine the smallest mirror radius r∗ m [see Eq. (3)] which allows the extraction of rotational energy from spinning Kerr black holes. (This critical mirror radius also marks the boundary between stable and unstable black-hole-mirror-field configurations.) As discussed above, the numerical results of [14] indicate that, for a given value of the spheroidal harmonic index l of the confined field, the equatorial m = l mode is characterized by the innermost location of the stationary mirror radius. We therefore focus our attention on these equatorial modes</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">38</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth emphasizing again that the mirror-like boundary condition (21) is valid for mirror radii in the xm ≪ 1 regime [see Eq. (18)]. Solving the resonance condition (21) for small and moderate values of the spheroidal harmonic index l, one finds xstat m (¯a, m</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">n = 1)/τ 1, see Table II. Thus, the stationary mirror radii presented in Table II are valid in the regime of rapidly-rotating (near-extremal) black holes with τ xstat m (¯a, m</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">n = 1) ≪ 1</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">We are interested here in the relation xstat m = xstat m (τ) to leading-order in the small parameter τ ≪ 1 (note that τ ≪ 1 corresponds to ¯a ≃ 1). We therefore take aω = m/2 + O(τ) and k = m+O(τ2) in Eqs. (12), (16), and (20). The leading-order values of the separation constants (the angular eigenvalues) δlm are given in Table II</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">40</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In the asymptotic m ≫ 1 regime, the angular separation constants δ are given by Eq. (39) below</subfield>
